{"key":"processedPost-10981560","value":{"id":10981560,"first":10980052,"last":10982437,"when":1251850703,"utime":"09/02/09 03:18 AM","content":"It's not a replacement for gypsum, which contains sulfur AND calcium, thus it provides those minerals without altering pH.&nbsp; Mycelium likes an acidic substrate, so if you're not using something that's already acidic such as coir and/or coffee grinds, add a bit of sulfur.&nbsp; Just know it's not a sub for gypsum, which should be available at the same place you got the sulfur.<br />RR","title":"Re: Garden Sulphur as compliment or substitute for gypsum","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}